Detects if conditions that always evaluate to TRUE. This is only triggered for if statements without an else clause, these are handled by unreachable_code.



Code in an if statement whose condition always evaluates to TRUE will always run. It clutters the code and makes it more difficult to read. In these cases, the if condition should be removed.
This rule does not have an automatic fix.



if (TRUE) {
  print("always true")
}

if (TRUE || ...) {
  print("always true")
}

if (!FALSE) {
  print("always true")
}
Use instead:
print("always true")

if (TRUE) {
  print("always true")
}

if (TRUE || ...) {
  print("always true")
}

if (!FALSE) {
  print("always true")
}
Use instead:
print("always true")

# In NAMESPACE: export(public_fn)

# In R/public.R:
public_fn &lt;- function(x) {
  check_character(x)
}

# In R/helper.R:
check_character &lt;- function(x) {
  stopifnot(is.character(x))
}
check_length &lt;- function(x, y) {
  stopifnot(length(x) == y)
}

# `public_fn()` is exported by the package, so it is considered used.
# `check_character()` isn't exported but used in `public_fn`.
# `check_length()` isn't exported but and isn't used anywhere, so it is
# reported.

Checks whether the index symbol in a for loop is already used anywhere in the sequence of the same for loop.



for (x in x) or for (x in foo(x)) are confusing to read and can lead to errors.



